<br>
The most important thing in leading a raid is to be LARGE AND IN CHARGE.  People who have been on raids with me know I spam stuff and sometimes in all caps so that I know I'm heard.  It's hard to get left behind when all of the sudden your screen fills up with &quot;MOVE UP&quot;, lol.<br>
<br>
If you aren't in charge, people will start giving orders that they think are best, but maybe not what you want.  Or contradicting orders.  Even if you don't know if you have the best solution, it is best 99% of the time to be firm and follow through with it.  Be open to suggestions, though, but ask those suggestions to come as /tells.  That way they won't be misconstrued as orders.<br>
<br>
Another thing that is VERY important is that the raid leader is responsible for everyone on the raid.  That means he/she makes sure the raid stays together long enough to get everyone's corpses.  Even if people can't help on the corpse runs, they should stay, unless real life calls.  You never know if we'll end up having to fight our way to the corpse.  Hold rolls on loot until everyone is back from death or LD.  Be one million times more concerned about the people than the loot.  With one exception:  completion of the raid GOAL &gt; all.  For example, get the toon rezzed so they can loot that epic piece before the corpse rots even if it will cause a total wipeout.  THEN you recover and grats on a successful raid.<br>
<br>
I've copied this over from the info section:<br>
<br>
RAID GUIDELINES<br>
<br>
The raid you plan should be for your level or lower. <br>
<br>
Ensure attendance by advertising your raid (Guild MOTD, News section, Calendar and forum) and planning far enough in advance for word to get around. <br>
<br>
Plan only one raid at a time. This reduces confusion and allows others a chance to plan raids. You can plan multiple raids and announce them, however they should be far enough apart to allow others to squeeze in their needs. <br>
<br>
Have clear goals and announce the goals to the raiding party so that everyone is on the same page. <br>
<br>
Announce how to handle loot prior to raid. Need before greed, alpha, first loot first serve, or magic dice rolling. <br>
<br>
Create chat channel with a name easy to spell or know (Example: /join Brewer {gnoll brewer raid in Blackburrow}) <br>
<br>
Choose group leaders who you know will conduct themselves well with you, or that you know personally <br>
<br>
Establish &quot;safe spots&quot; when moving to the raid area. Healers need to med to keep their mana. Oh yea, no mana, no heal. Same with other casters. <br>
<br>
Make sure everyone knows not to pass you unless running to next safe spot, and stand where people shouldn't pass. <br>
<br>
Know the area very well before you get there. Study maps on eqatlas and print them out. If possible, scope out the area before the raid. <br>
<br>
Explain politely how to use necessary things such as /assist and not to break mez to people who don't understand. Try to be patient with people who are following the rules and trying. <br>
<br>
You have the option to remove people from the raid who are transgressing or going against your commands in the raid. <br>
<br>
You are not required to wait for people who are late nor send them guides. This choice is at your discretion. <br>
